definition.value: The oxonium betaine of anthocyanidin 3,5-diglucoside arising from selective deprotonation of the 7-hydroxy group.
A phenolate anion that is the conjugate base of 2'-O-methyllicodione, obtained by deprotonation of the phenolic hydroxy group at position 4; major species at pH 7.3.
A phenolate anion that is the conjugate base of protoaphin aglucone, obtained by deprotonation of the phenolic hydroxy group at position 7'; major species at pH 7.3.
A peptide anion that is the conjugate base of any 5-L-glutamyl amino acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A phenolate anion that is the conjugate base of 2',4,4',6'-tetrahydroxychalcone, obtained by deprotonation of the phenolic hydroxy group at position 2'; major species at pH 7.3.
A 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoserine in which the acyl group is specified as oleoyl.
A phenolate anion that is the conjugate base of 2,3',4,6-tetrahydroxybenzophenone, obtained by deprotonation of the phenolic hydroxy group at position 2; major species at pH 7.3.
A macrolide antibiotic that is biosynthesised by Streptomyces venezuelae.
A monocarboxylic acid that is 2-hydroxy-2-methylpropanoic acid in which ther tertiary hydroxy group has been converted into the corresponding p-(1,2,3,4-tetrahydronaphthalen-1-yl)phenyl ether.
A 2-methyl-2-[4-(1,2,3,4-tetrahydronaphthalen-1-yl)phenoxy]propanoic acid that has R configuration at the chiral centre.
A 2-methyl-2-[4-(1,2,3,4-tetrahydronaphthalen-1-yl)phenoxy]propanoic acid that has S configuration at the chiral centre.
A twelve-membered macrolide antibiotic that is biosynthesised by Streptomyces venezuelae.
A (3R)-3-hydroxyacyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the 3-carboxy group of (3R)-3-carboxy-3-hydroxypropanoic acid.
An EC 1.1.1.* (oxidoreductase acting on donor CH-OH group, NAD(+) or NADP(+) acceptor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of 1-deoxy-D-xylulose-5-phosphate reductoisomerase (EC 1.1.1.267).
An organoammonium salt obtained by combining perindopril with one molar equivalent of L-arginine.
An amino acid zwitterion obtained from 4-oxoproline by transfer of a proton from the alpha-carboxy group to the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion that is the major structure at pH 7.3 of 5-amino-1-(5-phospho-D-ribosyl)imidazole-4-carboxylic acid.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion that is the major structure of isonocardicin A at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A phenolate anion that is the conjugate base of emodin, obtained by deprotonation of the phenolic hydroxy group at position 2; major species at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).

A tricarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the three carboxy groups as well as the 5-hydroxy group of pyrroloquinoline quinol; major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
An amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the amino to the carboxy group of L-3-oxoalanine; major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
An organic anion obtained by deprotonation of the two hydroxy groups of pulcherriminic acid; major species at pH 7.3.

A cyclic tetrapyrrole anion that is the conjugate base of magnesium protoporphyrin 13-monomethyl ester, formed by deprotonation of the carboxyethyl group at C-17; major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).

A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of  primary fluorescent chlorophyll catabolite resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group. Major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A carbohydrate acid derivative anion arising from deprotonation of the carboxy and 5-hydroxy groups of luteolin 7-O-beta-D-glucosiduronic acid; major species at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
Any N-acyl-D-amino acid obtained by the formal N-acylation of D-phenylalanine.
Any N-acyl-L-amino acid obtained by the formal N-acylation of L-phenylalanine.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of queuine, obtained by protonation of the secondary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of epoxyqueuine, obtained by protonation of the secondary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A 1-alkyl-2-acetyl-3-acyl-sn-glycerol in which the alkyl and acyl groups are specified as palmityl and linoleoyl.
A 1-alkyl-2-acetyl-3-acyl-sn-glycerol in which the alkyl and acyl groups are specified as palmityl and stearoyl.
A 1-alkyl-2-acetyl-3-acyl-sn-glycerol in which the alkyl and acyl groups are specified as palmityl and myristoyl.
A 1-alkyl-2-acetyl-3-acyl-sn-glycerol in which the alkyl and acyl groups are specified as palmityl and capryl.
A 1-alkyl-2-acetyl-3-acyl-sn-glycerol in which the alkyl and acyl groups are specified as palmityl and palmitoyl.
A 1-alkyl-2-acetyl-3-acyl-sn-glycerol in which the alkyl and acyl groups are specified as palmityl and lauroyl.
A 1-alkyl-2-acetyl-3-acyl-sn-glycerol in which the alkyl and acyl groups are specified as palmityl and capryloyl.
A triacyl-sn-glycerol in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl while that at position 3 is specifed as linoleoyl.
A triacyl-sn-glycerol in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl while that at position 3 is specifed as myristoyl.
A triacyl-sn-glycerol in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl while that at position 3 is specifed as lauroyl.
A triacyl-sn-glycerol in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl while that at position 3 is specifed as stearoyl.
A flavonoid oxoanion that is the conjugate base of 2'-hydroxyformononetin, obtained by deprotonation of the 7-hydroxy group. Major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A flavonoid oxoanion that is the conjugate base of formononetin, obtained by deprotonation of the 7-hydroxy group. Major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
An amino acid zwitterion resulting from a transfer of a proton from the carboxy group to the amino group of L-mimosine; major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
An alkanethiol that is hexane substituted at positions 1 and 3 by hydroxy and sulfanyl groups respectively.
A 3beta-sterol consisting of an ergostane skeleton with double bonds at positions 8(9) and 22.
A macrolide that is a novel secondary metabolite isolated from a New Zealand marine sponge, Mycale hentscheli.
